Note: ============================================================================
Note: JULIA TO HIR TRANSLATOR
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Translates Julia AST to High-level Intermediate Representation (HIR)
Note: Handles Julia-specific features:
Note: - Multiple dispatch and method specialization
Note: - Parametric types and type constraints
Note: - Metaprogramming and macro expansion
Note: - Module system and imports
Note: - Performance annotations and optimizations
Note: - Abstract types and composite types
Note: - Just-in-time compilation hints

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_nodes.runa" as HirNodes
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_builder.runa" as HirBuilder

Note: Local Julia AST node schema (fields used by translation logic; distinct from
Note: the real HIRNode in hir_nodes.runa which has node_type/value/children/etc).
Note: This represents the parsed Julia source AST input, NOT the HIR output.
@Reasoning:
Julia's AST contains many syntactically distinct constructs (modules,
function/method definitions, parametric type defs, comprehensions, macro
calls, type-annotated lets). One union record with optional fields lets a
single Match in translate_julia_node dispatch on .type without per-construct
node hierarchies, mirroring how Julia itself uses Expr(:head, args...).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
30+ optional fields. .type and .type_kind are dispatch discriminators;
.name/.function_name carry identifiers; .body/.expression/.value carry
nested ASTs; .parameters/.type_parameters/.arguments/.fields are List
handles; .literal_type tags primitive literals; .supertype/.base_type
are recursive JuliaIRNode handles for type-level expressions. Fields not
relevant to a given node kind are simply ignored by the translator.
@End Implementation

Type called "JuliaIRNode":
    type as String
    name as String
    body as Integer
    exports as Integer
    imports as Integer
    type_parameters as Integer
    parameters as Integer
    return_type as Integer
    where_clause as Integer
    function_name as String
    signature as Integer
    line_info as Integer
    type_kind as String
    fields as Integer
    is_mutable as Integer
    supertype as Integer
    arguments as Integer
    type_arguments as Integer
    keyword_arguments as Integer
    macro_name as String
    elements as Integer
    element_type as Integer
    dimensions as Integer
    expression as Integer
    iterators as Integer
    filters as Integer
    asserted_type as Integer
    variable as Integer
    iterable as Integer
    value as Integer
    literal_type as Integer
    base_type as JuliaIRNode
End Type

@Reasoning:
Minimal type-parameter record. Julia parametric types like Array{T,N} carry
zero or more such parameters; current translation only needs the parameter
name. Constraint info (where-clauses) is held on the parent function/struct
record, not here.
@End Reasoning

Type called "JuliaTypeParam":
    name as String
End Type

@Reasoning:
Function parameters in Julia carry an optional type annotation
(`x::Int64`). The annotation is itself a JuliaIRNode because Julia
type-expressions can be arbitrary (parametric, where-quantified, vararg).
Untyped parameters carry a null type_annotation.
@End Reasoning

Type called "JuliaFuncParam":
    name as String
    type_annotation as JuliaIRNode
End Type

@Reasoning:
The translation context bundles every piece of mutable state a Julia
translation pass needs: the HIR builder it appends to, the lexical
module/function stack, the type-parameter scope (for `where T` resolution),
local variable bindings, an instance cache for method specialization, a
macro-expansion cache, and the optimization knobs (`optimization_level`,
`world_age`) Julia exposes. Bundling avoids threading 10 separate
parameters through every translate_* call.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reference-counted record built via "a value of type" constructor in
create_julia_hir_context. Dictionaries are keyed by qualified Julia name;
performance_hints is a list of pragma strings collected from @inbounds /
@simd / @fastmath macros and consumed by the optimizer pass after
translation.
@End Implementation

Type called "JuliaToHIRContext":
    hir_builder as HIRBuilder
    current_module as String
    current_function as String
    type_parameters as List[String]
    local_variables as Dictionary[String, HIRNode]
    method_instances as Dictionary[String, HIRNode]
    macro_expansions as Dictionary[String, HIRNode]
    performance_hints as List[String]
    optimization_level as Integer
    world_age as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
The public entry point creates a fresh JuliaToHIRContext (which seeds the
"Main" module, optimisation level 2, world age 1), recursively translates the
Julia AST into HIR, and then runs optimize_julia_hir on the result. Running
the optimiser inside the entry rather than asking the caller to do it
guarantees that Julia-specific transforms (dispatch hint annotation, special
function recognition, array hot-path hints) are always applied; clients that
want unoptimised HIR for diagnostic purposes should call translate_julia_node
directly with their own context.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_julia_to_hir" that takes julia_ast as JuliaIRNode returns HIRNode:
    Note: Main entry point for Julia to HIR translation

    Let context be create_julia_hir_context
    Let hir_module be translate_julia_node with julia_ast and context

    Note: Perform post-translation optimizations
    Call optimize_julia_hir with hir_module and context

    Return hir_module
End Process

@Reasoning:
A fresh context establishes the "Main" module as the default lexical scope
(matching Julia's REPL behaviour) and seeds an optimization_level of 2
(-O2 equivalent) and world_age 1, which represents the empty
method-dispatch world prior to any user method definitions. Both knobs are
mutated as the translator visits `@optlevel` / method definitions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a new HIRBuilder, then constructs JuliaToHIRContext via the
struct-with-fields syntax. All five tracking maps (locals, methods, macros,
hints, params) start empty so the translator can populate them
incrementally.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_julia_hir_context" that takes nothing returns JuliaToHIRContext:
    Note: Create translation context for Julia to HIR

    Let hir_builder be create_hir_builder

    Return a value of type JuliaToHIRContext with
        hir_builder as hir_builder,
        current_module as "Main",
        current_function as null,
        type_parameters as a list containing nothing,
        local_variables as a dictionary containing nothing,
        method_instances as a dictionary containing nothing,
        macro_expansions as a dictionary containing nothing,
        performance_hints as a list containing nothing,
        optimization_level as 2,
        world_age as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Central dispatcher: every other translate_julia_* helper handles a single
construct, but the recursive structure of Julia ASTs means many helpers
need to re-translate child nodes whose kind is not statically known. This
function is the polymorphic entry point those helpers call back into.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
One large Match on node.type. Each arm forwards to the dedicated helper
(translate_julia_module, _function_def, _method_def, etc). Falls through
to an Otherwise branch that builds a generic HIR placeholder node for any
construct the translator does not yet specialise — keeps the pipeline
total rather than crashing on unknown shapes.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_julia_node" that takes node as JuliaIRNode, ctx as JuliaToHIRContext returns HIRNode:
    Note: Translate any Julia AST node to HIR

    Match node.type:
        When "Module":
            Return translate_julia_module with node and ctx
        When "FunctionDef":
            Return translate_julia_function_def with node and ctx
        When "MethodDef":
            Return translate_julia_method_def with node and ctx
        When "TypeDef":
            Return translate_julia_type_def with node and ctx
        When "AbstractTypeDef":
            Return translate_julia_abstract_type_def with node and ctx
        When "PrimitiveTypeDef":
            Return translate_julia_primitive_type_def with node and ctx
        When "StructDef":
            Return translate_julia_struct_def with node and ctx
        When "MacroDef":
            Return translate_julia_macro_def with node and ctx
        When "MacroCall":
            Return translate_julia_macro_call with node and ctx
        When "Assignment":
            Return translate_julia_assignment with node and ctx
        When "MethodCall":
            Return translate_julia_method_call with node and ctx
        When "FieldAccess":
            Return translate_julia_field_access with node and ctx
        When "ArrayAccess":
            Return translate_julia_array_access with node and ctx
        When "ArrayConstruction":
            Return translate_julia_array_construction with node and ctx
        When "TupleConstruction":
            Return translate_julia_tuple_construction with node and ctx
        When "TypeAssertion":
            Return translate_julia_type_assertion with node and ctx
        When "TypeParameterDecl":
            Return translate_julia_type_parameter with node and ctx
        When "WhereClause":
            Return translate_julia_where_clause with node and ctx
        When "UsingStatement":
            Return translate_julia_using_statement with node and ctx
        When "ImportStatement":
            Return translate_julia_import_statement with node and ctx
        When "ExportStatement":
            Return translate_julia_export_statement with node and ctx
        When "BinaryOperation":
            Return translate_julia_binary_operation with node and ctx
        When "UnaryOperation":
            Return translate_julia_unary_operation with node and ctx
        When "ComparisonChain":
            Return translate_julia_comparison_chain with node and ctx
        When "IfStatement":
            Return translate_julia_if_statement with node and ctx
        When "TryStatement":
            Return translate_julia_try_statement with node and ctx
        When "ForLoop":
            Return translate_julia_for_loop with node and ctx
        When "WhileLoop":
            Return translate_julia_while_loop with node and ctx
        When "BreakStatement":
            Return translate_julia_break_statement with node and ctx
        When "ContinueStatement":
            Return translate_julia_continue_statement with node and ctx
        When "ReturnStatement":
            Return translate_julia_return_statement with node and ctx
        When "ThrowStatement":
            Return translate_julia_throw_statement with node and ctx
        When "LambdaExpression":
            Return translate_julia_lambda_expression with node and ctx
        When "ComprehensionExpression":
            Return translate_julia_comprehension with node and ctx
        When "GeneratorExpression":
            Return translate_julia_generator with node and ctx
        When "QuoteExpression":
            Return translate_julia_quote_expression with node and ctx
        When "InterpolationExpression":
            Return translate_julia_interpolation with node and ctx
        When "SymbolLiteral":
            Return translate_julia_symbol_literal with node and ctx
        When "Identifier":
            Return translate_julia_identifier with node and ctx
        When "Literal":
            Return translate_julia_literal with node and ctx
        Otherwise:
            Return translate_generic_julia_node with node and ctx
    End Match
End Process

@Reasoning:
Modules are translated by saving and restoring ctx.current_module around the
recursive body translation. This save-restore pattern is necessary because
Julia allows nested module declarations and inner constructs (qualified
references, exports) must be resolved against the innermost enclosing module
at the point where they appear. Exports and imports are translated in source
order BEFORE the body so subsequent body references can see the populated
import map, matching Julia's actual resolution semantics.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_julia_module" that takes node as JuliaIRNode, ctx as JuliaToHIRContext returns HIRNode:
    Note: Translate Julia module definition

    Let module_name be node.name
    Let module_body be node.body
    Let exports be node.exports
    Let imports be node.imports

    Note: Create HIR module
    Let hir_module be create_hir_module with ctx.hir_builder and module_name

    Note: Set module context
    Let old_module be ctx.current_module
    Set ctx.current_module to module_name

    Note: Translate exports
    For Each export_item in exports:
        Let hir_export be translate_julia_export with export_item and ctx
        Call add_hir_export with hir_module and hir_export
    End For

    Note: Translate imports
    For Each import_item in imports:
        Let hir_import be translate_julia_import with import_item and ctx
        Call add_hir_import with hir_module and hir_import
    End For

    Note: Translate module body
    For Each stmt in module_body:
        Let hir_stmt be translate_julia_node with stmt and ctx
        Call add_hir_statement with hir_module and hir_stmt
    End For

    Note: Restore module context
    Set ctx.current_module to old_module

    Return hir_module
End Process

@Reasoning:
Julia functions translate into HIR functions that carry the type-parameter
list, where-clause constraints, parameter list with per-parameter type
annotations, and an optional return-type assertion. Type parameters are added
to ctx.type_parameters BEFORE translating the parameter list, body, or where
clause because each of those may reference the type parameters as bound names
that must resolve to a parameter slot rather than a free identifier. After the
body is translated we remove the type parameters from scope so they cannot
leak into sibling function definitions in the same module body.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Dispatch hint generation runs after the body to allow add_julia_dispatch_hints
to consult the fully-translated HIR body when synthesising specialisation
hints; the hints depend on which method-call shapes appear inside the function.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_julia_function_def" that takes node as JuliaIRNode, ctx as JuliaToHIRContext returns HIRNode:
    Note: Translate Julia function definition

    Let func_name be node.name
    Let type_params be node.type_parameters
    Let params be node.parameters
    Let return_type be node.return_type
    Let body be node.body
    Let where_clause be node.where_clause

    Note: Create HIR function
    Let hir_function be create_hir_function with ctx.hir_builder and func_name

    Note: Set function context
    Let old_function be ctx.current_function
    Set ctx.current_function to func_name

    Note: Translate type parameters
    If type_params is not equal to 0:
        For Each type_param as JuliaTypeParam in type_params:
            Let hir_type_param be translate_julia_type_parameter with type_param and ctx
            Call add_hir_type_parameter with hir_function and hir_type_param
            Add type_param.name to end of ctx.type_parameters
        End For
    End If

    Note: Translate where clause constraints
    If where_clause is not equal to 0:
        Let hir_constraints be translate_julia_where_clause with where_clause and ctx
        Call add_hir_constraints with hir_function and hir_constraints
    End If

    Note: Translate parameters
    For Each param as JuliaFuncParam in params:
        Let hir_param be translate_julia_parameter with param and ctx
        Call add_hir_parameter with hir_function and hir_param

        Note: Add to local variables
        Set ctx.local_variables at key param.name to hir_param
    End For

    Note: Translate return type
    If return_type is not equal to 0:
        Let hir_return_type be translate_julia_type_expression with return_type and ctx
        Call set_hir_return_type with hir_function and hir_return_type
    End If

    Note: Translate function body
    Let hir_body be translate_julia_node with body and ctx
    Call set_hir_function_body with hir_function and hir_body

    Note: Add method specialization hints
    Call add_julia_dispatch_hints with hir_function and params and ctx

    Note: Restore function context
    Set ctx.current_function to old_function

    Note: Clear type parameters from scope
    If type_params is not equal to 0:
        For Each type_param as JuliaTypeParam in type_params:
            Call remove_from_list with ctx.type_parameters and type_param.name
        End For
    End If

    Return hir_function
End Process

@Reasoning:
A 'method' in Julia is a single specialisation of a function for one argument
signature; functions are name-bound collections of methods that the runtime
dispatches between based on the runtime types of arguments. We translate by
building an HIR method node and registering it in the dispatch table via
add_method_to_dispatch_table, which lets downstream optimisation passes ask
"what are all the methods of this function?" without re-walking the AST. The
line_info is propagated to the HIR via set_hir_source_location so debugger
backends can map between Julia source positions and HIR positions.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_julia_method_def" that takes node as JuliaIRNode, ctx as JuliaToHIRContext returns HIRNode:
    Note: Translate Julia method definition (specific method for existing function)

    Let func_name be node.function_name
    Let signature be node.signature
    Let body be node.body
    Let line_info be node.line_info

    Note: Create HIR method
    Let hir_method be create_hir_method with ctx.hir_builder and func_name

    Note: Translate method signature
    Let hir_signature be translate_julia_method_signature with signature and ctx
    Call set_hir_method_signature with hir_method and hir_signature

    Note: Translate method body
    Let hir_body be translate_julia_node with body and ctx
    Call set_hir_method_body with hir_method and hir_body

    Note: Add method to dispatch table
    Call add_method_to_dispatch_table with hir_method and signature and ctx

    Note: Set source location for debugging
    Call set_hir_source_location with hir_method and line_info

    Return hir_method
End Process

@Reasoning:
Julia type declarations come in three shapes that share the same outer AST
form (`type ... end`) but have very different semantics: struct (composite
with fields), abstract (no fields, used as supertype only), and primitive
(fixed-bit-width bits-types). The type_kind sub-discriminator selects the
right specialised translator.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Match on node.type_kind. The Otherwise arm defaults to struct because
unrecognised kinds most often originate from a missing kind tag on a
field-bearing AST, and struct is the least-lossy fallback. Each specialised
translator owns its own HIR construction.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_julia_type_def" that takes node as JuliaIRNode, ctx as JuliaToHIRContext returns HIRNode:
    Note: Translate Julia type definition (struct, abstract type, or primitive type)

    Match node.type_kind:
        When "struct":
            Return translate_julia_struct_def with node and ctx
        When "abstract":
            Return translate_julia_abstract_type_def with node and ctx
        When "primitive":
            Return translate_julia_primitive_type_def with node and ctx
        Otherwise:
            Return translate_julia_struct_def with node and ctx
    End Match
End Process

@Reasoning:
Julia structs carry a mutability bit that affects whether field stores are
permitted after construction; we translate this into an HIR property so the
backend can reject illegal mutations and choose between stack and heap layout
strategies. Default constructors are generated AFTER field translation
because the constructor signature depends on the materialised field set; if
the source defined custom constructors elsewhere, the upstream parser emits
them as separate method definitions that the dispatcher in translate_julia_node
processes independently.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_julia_struct_def" that takes node as JuliaIRNode, ctx as JuliaToHIRContext returns HIRNode:
    Note: Translate Julia struct definition

    Let type_name be node.name
    Let type_params be node.type_parameters
    Let fields be node.fields
    Let is_mutable be node.is_mutable
    Let supertype be node.supertype

    Note: Create HIR struct type
    Let hir_struct be create_hir_struct_type with ctx.hir_builder and type_name

    Note: Set mutability
    Call set_hir_struct_mutable with hir_struct and is_mutable

    Note: Translate type parameters
    If type_params is not equal to 0:
        For Each type_param in type_params:
            Let hir_type_param be translate_julia_type_parameter with type_param and ctx
            Call add_hir_type_parameter with hir_struct and hir_type_param
        End For
    End If

    Note: Translate supertype
    If supertype is not equal to 0:
        Let hir_supertype be translate_julia_type_expression with supertype and ctx
        Call set_hir_supertype with hir_struct and hir_supertype
    End If

    Note: Translate fields
    For Each field in fields:
        Let hir_field be translate_julia_struct_field with field and ctx
        Call add_hir_struct_field with hir_struct and hir_field
    End For

    Note: Generate constructors if not explicitly defined
    Call generate_default_constructors with hir_struct and fields and ctx

    Return hir_struct
End Process

@Reasoning:
Method calls are the dispatch sites that drive Julia's multiple-dispatch
runtime: the actual method selected depends on the runtime types of every
argument, not just the receiver. We translate by recording the call shape
verbatim (function name + argument expressions) and then invoke
optimize_special_function_calls to recognise hot patterns like +(::Int,::Int)
or getindex(::Array,::Int) where the compiler can devirtualise the call at HIR
level. Generic calls remain dispatch-flexible and only specialise during
later monomorphisation.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_julia_method_call" that takes node as JuliaIRNode, ctx as JuliaToHIRContext returns HIRNode:
    Note: Translate Julia method call with multiple dispatch

    Let function_name be node.function_name
    Let arguments be node.arguments
    Let type_args be node.type_arguments
    Let keyword_args be node.keyword_arguments

    Note: Create HIR method call
    Let hir_call be create_hir_method_call with ctx.hir_builder and function_name

    Note: Translate arguments
    For Each arg in arguments:
        Let hir_arg be translate_julia_node with arg and ctx
        Call add_hir_call_argument with hir_call and hir_arg
    End For

    Note: Translate type arguments
    If type_args is not equal to 0:
        For Each type_arg in type_args:
            Let hir_type_arg be translate_julia_type_expression with type_arg and ctx
            Call add_hir_call_type_argument with hir_call and hir_type_arg
        End For
    End If

    Note: Translate keyword arguments
    If keyword_args is not equal to 0:
        For Each kw_arg in keyword_args:
            Let hir_kw_arg be translate_julia_keyword_argument with kw_arg and ctx
            Call add_hir_call_keyword_argument with hir_call and hir_kw_arg
        End For
    End If

    Note: Add dispatch information
    Call add_dispatch_metadata with hir_call and function_name and arguments and ctx

    Note: Check for special function calls that need optimization
    Call optimize_special_function_calls with hir_call and function_name and ctx

    Return hir_call
End Process

@Reasoning:
Julia macros are syntactic transforms applied before HIR generation, so by the
time the translator sees them they have either already been expanded by the
upstream parser or they are a small set of compiler-recognised performance
macros (@inbounds, @simd, @fastmath, @inline, @noinline, @generated, @time,
@allocated, @assert, @show) that we treat specially because they MAP to HIR
attributes rather than HIR code. Each recognised macro routes to a dedicated
translator that attaches the appropriate hint to the argument expressions;
unrecognised macros fall through to translate_generic_macro_call which keeps
the macro shape verbatim for the user to inspect.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_julia_macro_call" that takes node as JuliaIRNode, ctx as JuliaToHIRContext returns HIRNode:
    Note: Translate Julia macro call and expand

    Let macro_name be node.macro_name
    Let arguments be node.arguments

    Note: Handle special performance macros
    Match macro_name:
        When "@inbounds":
            Return translate_inbounds_macro with arguments and ctx
        When "@simd":
            Return translate_simd_macro with arguments and ctx
        When "@fastmath":
            Return translate_fastmath_macro with arguments and ctx
        When "@inline":
            Return translate_inline_macro with arguments and ctx
        When "@noinline":
            Return translate_noinline_macro with arguments and ctx
        When "@generated":
            Return translate_generated_macro with arguments and ctx
        When "@time":
            Return translate_time_macro with arguments and ctx
        When "@allocated":
            Return translate_allocated_macro with arguments and ctx
        When "@assert":
            Return translate_assert_macro with arguments and ctx
        When "@show":
            Return translate_show_macro with arguments and ctx
        Otherwise:
            Return translate_generic_macro_call with node and ctx
    End Match
End Process

@Reasoning:
Array literals translate into an HIR array construction node that carries the
element type (if explicitly written, e.g. Int[1,2,3]), the dimensions (for
multi-dimensional constructors like [1 2 ; 3 4]), and each element subtree.
The dimensions field is crucial because Julia's row-major bracketed syntax
encodes 2-D arrays in a way that text reconstruction loses, so we capture
dimensions up front from the AST. add_array_optimization_hints runs after
element translation to recognise homogeneous-type literals where SIMD-friendly
storage layouts can be selected.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_julia_array_construction" that takes node as JuliaIRNode, ctx as JuliaToHIRContext returns HIRNode:
    Note: Translate Julia array construction

    Let elements be node.elements
    Let element_type be node.element_type
    Let dimensions be node.dimensions

    Note: Create HIR array construction
    Let hir_array be create_hir_array_construction with ctx.hir_builder

    Note: Translate element type
    If element_type is not equal to 0:
        Let hir_element_type be translate_julia_type_expression with element_type and ctx
        Call set_hir_array_element_type with hir_array and hir_element_type
    End If

    Note: Set dimensions
    If dimensions is not equal to 0:
        Call set_hir_array_dimensions with hir_array and dimensions
    End If

    Note: Translate elements
    For Each element in elements:
        Let hir_element be translate_julia_node with element and ctx
        Call add_hir_array_element with hir_array and hir_element
    End For

    Note: Add array optimization hints
    Call add_array_optimization_hints with hir_array and elements and ctx

    Return hir_array
End Process

@Reasoning:
Array comprehensions ([expr for var in iter if filter]) are kept in their
high-level comprehension form rather than desugared to a manual loop at HIR
level because loop optimisations (pre-allocation sizing, fusion, type
specialisation) need to see the comprehension as a unit. The HIR record holds
the body expression, the iterator list (multiple 'for' clauses chain into
nested loops), and the filter list (one or more 'if' clauses applied to each
combined iteration tuple). Filters are emitted as a list because Julia allows
multiple 'if' clauses; they are ANDed together at codegen time.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_julia_comprehension" that takes node as JuliaIRNode, ctx as JuliaToHIRContext returns HIRNode:
    Note: Translate Julia array comprehension

    Let expression be node.expression
    Let iterators be node.iterators
    Let filters be node.filters

    Note: Create HIR comprehension
    Let hir_comprehension be create_hir_comprehension with ctx.hir_builder

    Note: Translate expression
    Let hir_expr be translate_julia_node with expression and ctx
    Call set_hir_comprehension_expression with hir_comprehension and hir_expr

    Note: Translate iterators
    For Each iterator in iterators:
        Let hir_iterator be translate_julia_iterator with iterator and ctx
        Call add_hir_comprehension_iterator with hir_comprehension and hir_iterator
    End For

    Note: Translate filters
    If filters is not equal to 0:
        For Each filter in filters:
            Let hir_filter be translate_julia_node with filter and ctx
            Call add_hir_comprehension_filter with hir_comprehension and hir_filter
        End For
    End If

    Note: Add comprehension optimization hints
    Call add_comprehension_optimization_hints with hir_comprehension and ctx

    Return hir_comprehension
End Process

@Reasoning:
'expr::Type' assertions in Julia are runtime type checks that simultaneously
inform the type inferencer of the expression's narrowed type. We preserve both
the underlying expression and the asserted type as siblings on an HIR
assertion node, with add_type_assertion_hints attaching a strong type narrowing
hint that downstream passes use to specialise the surrounding code. The
assertion is NOT lowered into an if-throw pair at HIR level so that the
compiler can elide the runtime check when type inference proves it
unnecessary; lowering happens during code generation.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_julia_type_assertion" that takes node as JuliaIRNode, ctx as JuliaToHIRContext returns HIRNode:
    Note: Translate Julia type assertion (::Type)

    Let expression be node.expression
    Let asserted_type be node.asserted_type

    Note: Create HIR type assertion
    Let hir_assertion be create_hir_type_assertion with ctx.hir_builder

    Note: Translate expression
    Let hir_expr be translate_julia_node with expression and ctx
    Call set_hir_assertion_expression with hir_assertion and hir_expr

    Note: Translate asserted type
    Let hir_type be translate_julia_type_expression with asserted_type and ctx
    Call set_hir_assertion_type with hir_assertion and hir_type

    Note: Add type assertion optimization hints
    Call add_type_assertion_hints with hir_assertion and hir_type and ctx

    Return hir_assertion
End Process

@Reasoning:
For-loops in Julia bind a single variable to successive elements of any
iterable; this translator captures the iteration variable, the iterable
expression, and the loop body without rewriting them into a while-with-index
form because the HIR keeps the for-loop shape so analyze_simd_opportunities
can pattern-match against canonical ranges (1:N, eachindex(...)) for
vectorisation. add_loop_optimization_hints inspects the iterable to attach
loop-bound information when statically determinable, which feeds bound-check
elimination later in the pipeline.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_julia_for_loop" that takes node as JuliaIRNode, ctx as JuliaToHIRContext returns HIRNode:
    Note: Translate Julia for loop

    Let variable be node.variable
    Let iterable be node.iterable
    Let body be node.body

    Note: Create HIR for loop
    Let hir_for be create_hir_for_loop with ctx.hir_builder

    Note: Translate loop variable
    Let hir_var be translate_julia_identifier with variable and ctx
    Call set_hir_for_variable with hir_for and hir_var

    Note: Translate iterable
    Let hir_iterable be translate_julia_node with iterable and ctx
    Call set_hir_for_iterable with hir_for and hir_iterable

    Note: Translate body
    Let hir_body be translate_julia_node with body and ctx
    Call set_hir_for_body with hir_for and hir_body

    Note: Add loop optimization hints
    Call add_loop_optimization_hints with hir_for and iterable and ctx

    Note: Check for SIMD opportunities
    Call analyze_simd_opportunities with hir_for and body and ctx

    Return hir_for
End Process

@Reasoning:
Julia literals carry semantic type information that matters for downstream
optimization (e.g. Int64 vs Float64 selects different arithmetic
instructions). The translator must preserve the literal_type tag rather
than letting it be inferred, because integer overflow / float precision
behaviour differ.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates a HIR literal with the raw value, then matches literal_type and
sets a concrete HIR type name: Integer -> Int64, Float -> Float64, Char ->
Char, Boolean -> Bool, Symbol -> Symbol, String -> String. Unrecognised
literal kinds fall through to "Any" so the translator stays total.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_julia_literal" that takes node as JuliaIRNode, ctx as JuliaToHIRContext returns HIRNode:
    Note: Translate Julia literal values

    Let value be node.value
    Let literal_type be node.literal_type

    Note: Create HIR literal
    Let hir_literal be create_hir_literal with ctx.hir_builder and value

    Note: Set literal type
    Match literal_type:
        When "Integer":
            Call set_hir_literal_type with hir_literal and "Int64"
        When "Float":
            Call set_hir_literal_type with hir_literal and "Float64"
        When "String":
            Call set_hir_literal_type with hir_literal and "String"
        When "Character":
            Call set_hir_literal_type with hir_literal and "Char"
        When "Boolean":
            Call set_hir_literal_type with hir_literal and "Bool"
        When "Symbol":
            Call set_hir_literal_type with hir_literal and "Symbol"
        Otherwise:
            Call set_hir_literal_type with hir_literal and "Any"
    End Match

    Return hir_literal
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PERFORMANCE MACRO TRANSLATIONS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
@inbounds wraps an expression in an HIR block that promises every array
indexing inside the expression is in-bounds, allowing the backend to remove
bounds checks. We translate the inner expression first (so any nested macros
or method calls translate normally), then attach the "no_bounds_check" hint
on the wrapper block; backend passes consult the hint when emitting array
access code. This contract is unsafe: violating it is undefined behaviour,
matching Julia's @inbounds semantics exactly.
@End Reasoning
@Security_Scope:
@inbounds disables safety checks; the trustworthiness of the wrapped code is
the user's responsibility. Translator does not add any extra validation.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "translate_inbounds_macro" that takes arguments as List[JuliaIRNode], ctx as JuliaToHIRContext returns HIRNode:
    Note: Translate @inbounds macro for bounds check elimination

    Note: Get the expression to execute without bounds checking
    Let expression be arguments at index 0

    Note: Create HIR inbounds block
    Let hir_inbounds be create_hir_inbounds_block with ctx.hir_builder

    Note: Translate expression with bounds checking disabled
    Let hir_expr be translate_julia_node with expression and ctx
    Call set_hir_inbounds_expression with hir_inbounds and hir_expr

    Note: Add optimization hint
    Call add_hir_optimization_hint with hir_inbounds and "no_bounds_check"

    Return hir_inbounds
End Process

@Reasoning:
@simd marks a loop as a candidate for SIMD vectorisation. The translator
wraps the loop in an HIR SIMD block and attaches both "vectorize" and "simd"
hints; the dual hinting is intentional - "vectorize" is the backend-agnostic
request and "simd" is the architecture-specific permission to emit SIMD
instructions specifically. The macro contract permits the compiler to assume
loop iterations are independent enough to reorder, which the user has
asserted by writing @simd.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_simd_macro" that takes arguments as List[JuliaIRNode], ctx as JuliaToHIRContext returns HIRNode:
    Note: Translate @simd macro for vectorization

    Note: Get the loop to vectorize
    Let loop_expr be arguments at index 0

    Note: Create HIR SIMD block
    Let hir_simd be create_hir_simd_block with ctx.hir_builder

    Note: Translate loop with SIMD hints
    Let hir_loop be translate_julia_node with loop_expr and ctx
    Call set_hir_simd_loop with hir_simd and hir_loop

    Note: Add vectorization hints
    Call add_hir_optimization_hint with hir_simd and "vectorize"
    Call add_hir_optimization_hint with hir_simd and "simd"

    Return hir_simd
End Process

@Reasoning:
@fastmath enables IEEE-relaxed floating-point transformations: reassociation,
no-NaN, no-Inf, no-signed-zero, contraction. The translator attaches four
separate hints rather than a single "fastmath" hint so backend passes can
opt into individual relaxations selectively - some targets support reassoc
but not no_nans, for example. The user has accepted that exact IEEE semantics
no longer hold inside the block; we do NOT silently propagate the hints into
nested macros, only into the immediate expression.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_fastmath_macro" that takes arguments as List[JuliaIRNode], ctx as JuliaToHIRContext returns HIRNode:
    Note: Translate @fastmath macro for aggressive math optimizations

    Note: Get the expression for fast math
    Let expression be arguments at index 0

    Note: Create HIR fastmath block
    Let hir_fastmath be create_hir_fastmath_block with ctx.hir_builder

    Note: Translate expression with fast math enabled
    Let hir_expr be translate_julia_node with expression and ctx
    Call set_hir_fastmath_expression with hir_fastmath and hir_expr

    Note: Add fast math optimization hints
    Call add_hir_optimization_hint with hir_fastmath and "fast_math"
    Call add_hir_optimization_hint with hir_fastmath and "reassoc"
    Call add_hir_optimization_hint with hir_fastmath and "no_nans"
    Call add_hir_optimization_hint with hir_fastmath and "no_infs"

    Return hir_fastmath
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HELPER FUNCTIONS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
For each function parameter whose declaration carries an explicit type
annotation, we emit a "specialized_for_<TypeName>" hint on the HIR function.
These hints let downstream monomorphisation choose a single concrete method
instance over the generic one when call-site type analysis matches the
annotation. A final "multiple_dispatch" hint is added unconditionally so even
fully-untyped functions are tagged for the dispatch optimiser to consider.
The hint vocabulary is open-ended; backends ignore hints they do not
recognise.
@End Reasoning
Process called "add_julia_dispatch_hints" that takes hir_function as HIRNode, params as List[JuliaIRNode], ctx as JuliaToHIRContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Add method dispatch hints for optimization

    Note: Analyze parameter types for dispatch hints
    For Each param as JuliaFuncParam in params:
        If param.type_annotation is not equal to 0:
            Let type_hint be "specialized_for_" joined with param.type_annotation.name
            Call add_hir_optimization_hint with hir_function and type_hint
        End If
    End For

    Note: Add general dispatch hint
    Call add_hir_optimization_hint with hir_function and "multiple_dispatch"
End Process

@Reasoning:
A small fixed set of Julia function names map to well-known semantic
categories that backend passes optimise specifically: the four arithmetic
operators get an "arithmetic_op" tag (enabling fold-on-constant and target
ISA selection), getindex/setindex! get array access tags (enabling bounds
elision when paired with @inbounds), and length/size get an "array_property"
tag (enabling load hoisting in loops). Any name not in this list passes
through untagged because adding noise hints would just dilute the signal.
@End Reasoning
Process called "optimize_special_function_calls" that takes hir_call as HIRNode, function_name as String, ctx as JuliaToHIRContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Add optimization hints for special Julia functions

    Match function_name:
        When "+":
            Call add_hir_optimization_hint with hir_call and "arithmetic_op"
        When "-":
            Call add_hir_optimization_hint with hir_call and "arithmetic_op"
        When "*":
            Call add_hir_optimization_hint with hir_call and "arithmetic_op"
        When "/":
            Call add_hir_optimization_hint with hir_call and "arithmetic_op"
        When "getindex":
            Call add_hir_optimization_hint with hir_call and "array_access"
        When "setindex!":
            Call add_hir_optimization_hint with hir_call and "array_assignment"
        When "length":
            Call add_hir_optimization_hint with hir_call and "array_property"
        When "size":
            Call add_hir_optimization_hint with hir_call and "array_property"
        Otherwise:
            Note: No special optimization hints
    End Match
End Process

@Reasoning:
We attach three hint kinds: "literal_array" + "const_fold" when every element
is a literal (the entire construction can be folded to a static constant at
compile time), "small_array" when the literal length is at most 32 (the
threshold below which stack allocation is generally a win), and
"array_construction" unconditionally so backend passes can locate every
construction site uniformly. The threshold of 32 is chosen to match typical
cache-line/spill thresholds; revisiting it requires profiling, not
guesswork.
@End Reasoning
Process called "add_array_optimization_hints" that takes hir_array as HIRNode, elements as List[JuliaIRNode], ctx as JuliaToHIRContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Add optimization hints for array construction

    Note: Check if all elements are literals
    Let all_literals be true
    For Each element as JuliaIRNode in elements:
        If element.type is not equal to "Literal":
            Set all_literals to false
            Break
        End If
    End For

    If all_literals:
        Call add_hir_optimization_hint with hir_array and "literal_array"
        Call add_hir_optimization_hint with hir_array and "const_fold"
    End If

    Note: Check array size for small array optimization
    If length of elements is less than or equal to 32:
        Call add_hir_optimization_hint with hir_array and "small_array"
    End If

    Note: Add general array construction hint
    Call add_hir_optimization_hint with hir_array and "array_construction"
End Process

@Reasoning:
After the full HIR module has been built, this pass runs Julia-specific
analyses that need the complete module in hand: method specialisation
opportunity analysis (cross-method call patterns), type stability analysis
(which fields/locals have type-invariant assignments), and inlining
candidate identification (small/leaf methods). Each sub-analysis attaches
hints to existing nodes rather than mutating structure, so the optimiser can
be re-run incrementally as more HIR is added (e.g. by additional source
files in the same module).
@End Reasoning
Process called "optimize_julia_hir" that takes hir_module as HIRNode, ctx as JuliaToHIRContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Perform post-translation HIR optimizations

    Note: Add method specialization hints
    Call analyze_method_specialization_opportunities with hir_module and ctx

    Note: Add type stability information
    Call analyze_type_stability with hir_module and ctx

    Note: Mark functions for inlining
    Call analyze_inlining_opportunities with hir_module and ctx

    Note: Add memory layout hints
    Call analyze_memory_layout_opportunities with hir_module and ctx
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TYPE EXPRESSION TRANSLATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Julia type expressions are themselves an AST sublanguage with bare names,
parametric instantiations (Array{T,N}), unions (Union{T1,T2}), where-clause
quantifiers (T where T<:Number), variadic types (Vararg{T,N}), and type
parameter references. Each variety routes to a dedicated translator because
the HIR representation diverges substantially: a bare name becomes a type
reference, a union becomes a sum type, a where-clause becomes a constrained
type expression. The Otherwise fallback returns the HIR Any type rather than
nil so that downstream type-checking always has SOMETHING to compare against.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_julia_type_expression" that takes type_expr as JuliaIRNode, ctx as JuliaToHIRContext returns HIRNode:
    Note: Translate Julia type expressions

    Match type_expr.type:
        When "TypeName":
            Return translate_julia_type_name with type_expr and ctx
        When "ParametricType":
            Return translate_julia_parametric_type with type_expr and ctx
        When "UnionType":
            Return translate_julia_union_type with type_expr and ctx
        When "WhereType":
            Return translate_julia_where_type with type_expr and ctx
        When "VarargType":
            Return translate_julia_vararg_type with type_expr and ctx
        When "TypeParameter":
            Return translate_julia_type_parameter_ref with type_expr and ctx
        Otherwise:
            Return create_hir_any_type with ctx.hir_builder
    End Match
End Process

@Reasoning:
Simplest case of type-expression translation: a bare name like `Int64` or
`String`. Wrapped in a dedicated helper so the type-expression dispatcher
can call it uniformly alongside parametric/where/vararg cases.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Pulls the name field and builds a single HIR type-reference node via
create_hir_type_reference. No further resolution happens here — the HIR
builder owns name->declaration binding.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_julia_type_name" that takes type_expr as JuliaIRNode, ctx as JuliaToHIRContext returns HIRNode:
    Note: Translate simple type name

    Let type_name be type_expr.name
    Return create_hir_type_reference with ctx.hir_builder and type_name
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parametric type translation must preserve both the base type name and the
ordered list of type arguments because Julia's monomorphization and
multiple dispatch both key on the full applied form. Array{Int64,2} and
Array{Float64,2} produce distinct specialisations.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads .base_type (itself a JuliaIRNode with .name) and .type_parameters
(list of type expressions). Builds a HIR parametric type with the base
name and appends each translated parameter via add_hir_type_parameter,
recursively translating parameters through translate_julia_type_expression
so nested parametrics work correctly.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_julia_parametric_type" that takes type_expr as JuliaIRNode, ctx as JuliaToHIRContext returns HIRNode:
    Note: Translate parametric type like Array{Int64, 2}

    Let base_type be type_expr.base_type
    Let type_params be type_expr.type_parameters

    Let hir_parametric_type be create_hir_parametric_type with ctx.hir_builder and base_type.name

    For Each param in type_params:
        Let hir_param be translate_julia_type_expression with param and ctx
        Call add_hir_type_parameter with hir_parametric_type and hir_param
    End For

    Return hir_parametric_type
End Process

Note: Entry point for Julia to HIR translation
@Reasoning:
Public, stable name for use by the translation driver. Hides the internal
context-creating translate_julia_to_hir so callers do not need to know
about JuliaToHIRContext.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Single forwarding call into translate_julia_to_hir. Context creation,
optimization passes, and dispatch-table population are all handled
downstream.
@End Implementation

Process called "julia_to_hir" that takes julia_ast as JuliaIRNode returns HIRNode:
    Return translate_julia_to_hir with julia_ast
End Process